Added Logger.logStackTrace() method.

You should use this method over Throwable.printStackTrace() to ensure
that the stack trace is printed both to the console and to the log file.
I have designed it to print the stack trace in a similar style as the
printStackTrace() method (at least for the version of Java I am using).

All printStackTrace() calls have been replaced with
Logger.logStackTrace() calls except for the runnable modules that are
not RMG.

added a backup connectivity check approach; also refactored some parts of QMTP

original approach with OpenBabel may suggest a mismatch when there isn't one due to either OpenBabel segmentation fault (e.g. http://sourceforge.net/tracker/?func=detail&aid=3417992&group_id=40728&atid=428740) producing empty InChI or tolerances that are too tight (e.g. InChI=1/C10H12O2/c1-2-6-9(5-1)11-12-10-7-3-4-8-10/h1,7H,2-4,6,8H2); if there is a mismatch using OpenBabel approach, print a warning and go to the backup check using MoleCoor
code was refactored to reduce repeated code
also there was a minor change to whether InChI vs. modified InChI was used in certain parts of the code

modifications to allow simultaneous jobs to use the same QMfiles folder

previously, due to overlapping filenames, multiple jobs couldn't simultaneously use the same QMTP folder
because of the way InChIs are generated, however, simultaneous jobs should still use separate InChI folders via having separate working directories; a similar, though more minor, issue is associated with the 2Dmolfiles and 3Dmolfiles folders, which are cleared at the start of a new run; thus, the recommended approach is to create a link to the "master" QMfiles folder from each working directory
symminput.txt is replaced with [name].symm; RMGrunCHKfile.chk is replaced with the Gaussian default, deleted at the end of each run; inputkeywords.txt is replaced with a command-line argument, similar to what had been done with MOPAC

QMTP .hold file changes.

We now delete the hold files on exiting RMG, so that you don't end up
freezing a subsequent run waiting for ever for a something to finish a
job that's not running.

We clear the hold on the first success, and on the last failure.

I have integrated the bank database to Plutus. The user information and account
threshold in the database can be updated.  For the purpose of Plutus
development, I have added a backdoor in the login menu, so we can directly
access to the Bank database and perform debug and maintainance. Currently, our
database simulation can serve and test three activities: simulation, update and
retrieval.

Once the bank database is simulated, it stayed in the private storage of app
until the deletion of app. I have added the bank database manager as private
members in each activity, so each activity can access to the database as in read
mode. There are two activities having the both read and write mode:
UpdateAccountSettingActivity and BankDatabaseSimulationActivity. When an
activity is on pause, we close the connection to the database. When an activity
is on resume, we open the connection as either read of read-write mode
accordingly.

I migrated the modification to our Plutus implementation such that the
getTransactionTableCursor() would now return a transaction table, where each
transaction is also assoicated with either checking or saving account for a
particular user. I have only tested the modification in the test bank database
workspace, but I will test it later on.

I inserted a code snippet in User.java and provide an example of fetching the
type of bank account from the usr's transaction table. Hopefully, everything
will work out well.
